vscode-docker.walkthrough.dockerStart.de: Learn about Docker and the Docker extension for Visual Studio Code
vscode-docker.walkthrough.dockerStart.op:
Open a workspace folder to get started with Docker extension features.
[Open Folder](command:workbench.action.files.openFolder)

Open a workspace folder to get started with Docker extension features.
[Open Folder](command:workbench.action.files.openFileFolder)
vscode-docker.walkthrough.dockerStart.sc:
A Dockerfile contains the instructions to assemble an image containing your app and its dependencies. Using this image to run your app in a container creates a production-like, reproducible runtime environment.

IntelliSense support for authoring your Dockerfile is provided.
[Add Docker Files](command:vscode-docker.configure)
vscode-docker.walkthrough.dockerStart.bu:
The Docker extension makes it simple to build your image.
[Build Image](command:vscode-docker.images.build)
vscode-docker.walkthrough.dockerStart.ru:
You can run any image on your system including those you've built with a Dockerfile.
[Run Image](command:vscode-docker.images.run)
vscode-docker.walkthrough.dockerStart.do:
The Docker Explorer makes it easy to manage, troubleshoot, and deploy containerized applications. The Docker Explorer shows a number of Docker resources such as containers, images, volumes, networks, and container registries.

The right-click menu provides access to commonly used commands for each resource type.
[Open Docker Explorer](command:workbench.view.extension.dockerView)
vscode-docker.walkthrough.dockerStart.pu: Push an Image to a Container Registry

The Docker Extension allows you to push your Docker image to Docker Hub, Azure Container Registries and other registry providers.
[Push an Image](command:vscode-docker.images.push)
vscode-docker.walkthrough.dockerStart.az:
The Docker extension helps you deploy your containerized applications and take advantage of a fully-managed platform using Azure App Service. Prior to deployment, the image must be uploaded to either Azure Container Registry or Docker Hub.

After a successful deployment, select **Open Site** in the notification. Your container is running in Azure!
[Deploy](command:vscode-docker.registries.deployImageToAzure)
vscode-docker.walkthrough.dockerStart.le:
Great job! You've now completed Getting Started with Docker. But don't stop here! There are plenty of ways to become more proficient building containerized applications using the Docker extension.

For example, you can [debug a container](https://code.visualstudio.com/docs/containers/debug-common), or [run multiple containers](https://code.visualstudio.com/docs/containers/docker-compose) at once using Docker Compose.

Check out our [documentation](https://code.visualstudio.com/docs/containers/overview) to make the most of the Docker extension for VS Code!
